05728nam a22009015i 9780812205688DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013956418  a(OCoLC)979741050  a97808122056887 a10.9783/97808122056882doi  a(DE-B1597)449407  a(OCoLC)794700698  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a363.320956942231 aOchs, Juliana, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSecurity and Suspicion :bAn Ethnography of Everyday Life in Israel /cJuliana Ochs. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b13 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Ethnography of Political Violence00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAuthor’s Note -- tIntroduction: The Practice of Everyday Security -- tChapter 1. A Genealogy of Israeli Security -- tChapter 2. Senses of Security: Rebuilding Café Hillel -- tChapter 3. Pahad: Fear as Corporeal Politics -- tChapter 4. Embodying Suspicion -- tChapter 5. Projecting Security in the City -- tChapter 6. On IKEA and Army Boots: The Domestication of Security -- tChapter 7. Seeing, Walking, Securing: Tours of Israel’s Separation Wall -- tEpilogue: Real Fantasies of Security -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Israel, gates, fences, and walls encircle public spaces while guards scrutinize, inspect, and interrogate. With a population constantly aware of the possibility of suicide bombings, Israel is defined by its culture of security. Security and Suspicion is a closely drawn ethnographic study of the way Israeli Jews experience security in their everyday lives.Observing security concerns through an anthropological lens, Juliana Ochs investigates the relationship between perceptions of danger and the political strategies of the state. Ochs argues that everyday security practices create exceptional states of civilian alertness that perpetuate—rather than mitigate—national fear and ongoing violence. In Israeli cities, customers entering gated urban cafés open their handbags for armed security guards and parents circumnavigate feared neighborhoods to deliver their children safely to school. Suspicious objects appear to be everywhere, as Israelis internalize the state's vigilance for signs of potential suicide bombers. Fear and suspicion not only permeate political rhetoric, writes Ochs, but also condition how people see, the way they move, and the way they relate to Palestinians. Ochs reveals that in Israel everyday practices of security—in the home, on commutes to work, or in cafés and restaurants—are as much a part of conflict as soldiers and military checkpoints.Based on intensive fieldwork in Israel during the second intifada, Security and Suspicion charts a new approach to issues of security while contributing to our appreciation of the subtle dynamics of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict. This book offers a way to understand why security propagates the very fears and suspicions it is supposed to reduce.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArab-Israeli conflictxInfluence. 0aSurvivalxPsychological aspects. 0aSurvivalzIsraelxPsychological aspects. 0aTerrorismxPrevention. 0aTerrorismxPsychological aspects. 0aTerrorismzIsraelxPrevention. 0aTerrorismzIsraelxPsychological aspects. 4aHuman Rights. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aFolklore.  aHuman Rights.  aLaw.  aLinguistics.  aPublic Policy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook pack